FIN SYSTEM PROMPTS & AGENT ARCHITECTURE
Complete Specification for Multi-Agent Financial AI Assistant

📋 DOCUMENTS IN THIS PACKAGE
This folder contains the complete system prompt specification and implementation guide for Fin's three AI agents:
1. 01_investment_agent_system_prompt.md
The portfolio optimization agent that analyzes holdings, identifies risks, and recommends rebalancing trades.
Key responsibilities:

Analyze diversification and concentration risk
Identify tax-loss harvesting opportunities
Recommend rebalancing with quantified impact
Educate on asset allocation and fees

Output: Markdown response with embedded JSON confidence scores
Triggers when: User asks about portfolio, wants recommendations, or connects Alpaca

2. 02_debt_agent_system_prompt.md
The loan optimization specialist that helps users eliminate debt strategically.
Key responsibilities:

Analyze payoff strategies (Avalanche vs Snowball)
Identify consolidation and refinancing opportunities
Resolve the critical "debt vs investment" dilemma
Recommend optimal payoff timeline with cashflow impact

Output: Clear recommendations with before/after projections
Triggers when: User asks about debt, connects Plaid, or wants payoff strategy

3. 03_retirement_agent_system_prompt.md
The retirement planning specialist focused on 401(k) optimization and contribution strategy.
Key responsibilities:

Calculate retirement readiness (funded %)
Maximize employer match (free money priority)
Optimize account types (Traditional vs Roth)
Project retirement income and identify gaps

Output: Actionable recommendations with retirement impact
Triggers when: User asks about retirement, 401(k), or retirement readiness

4. 04_user_context_file_schema.md
The data structure that gets passed to agents at the beginning of every conversation.
Contains:

User profile (age, income, risk tolerance)
Current portfolio and debts
Financial goals and retirement accounts
Behavioral patterns (acceptance rate, execution speed)
Past decisions and agent learning

Size: ~1-2KB per user (~100 tokens), injected as part of system prompt
Updated: After every user vote, daily data refreshes, and major life changes

5. 05_implementation_guide.md
Step-by-step instructions for backend developers integrating these prompts into FastAPI + Ollama.
Covers:

How to load and inject system prompts
How to fetch and pass user context
How to parse agent responses
How to update context after votes
Deployment with Docker Compose
Testing and debugging


🎯 QUICK OVERVIEW: HOW IT WORKS
User Journey
1. User logs in to Fin
   ↓
2. User clicks "Get Investment Recommendations"
   ↓
3. Backend loads Investment Agent system prompt
   ↓
4. Backend loads User Context File (portfolio, goals, past decisions)
   ↓
5. Backend injects context into system message
   ↓
6. Backend sends to Ollama (local LLM)
   ↓
7. Ollama processes with Investment Agent logic (C.O.R.E. framework)
   ↓
8. Agent generates recommendation with confidence scores
   ↓
9. Backend parses JSON response
   ↓
10. Frontend displays recommendation with vote buttons
    ↓
11. User votes: Accept / Reject / Defer
    ↓
12. Backend updates User Context File with new behavioral data
    ↓
13. Next recommendation uses updated context (more personalized)
Key Design Principles
🔐 Privacy First

All data stays on user's local machine
No cloud transmission
Encrypted API credentials
Only local LLM inference

🤖 Multi-Agent Coordination

Three independent agents, each specialized
Share common User Context File
Agents coordinate through updated context, not direct communication
Each agent has own system prompt + behavioral guidelines

📊 Personalization via Context

Agents read user's past decisions
Agents learn from acceptance/execution patterns
Agents adapt confidence scores based on user preferences
Behavioral patterns influence recommendation style

🎓 Transparency

Every recommendation includes reasoning
Confidence scores show where uncertainty lies
Trade-offs are explicit (what could go wrong)
Disclaimers are always included

🔄 Continuous Improvement

After every vote, context file is updated
Agents see learning from past interactions
Recommendation quality measured (did prediction match outcome?)
Behavioral patterns refined over time


📐 SYSTEM PROMPT STRUCTURE
All three agent prompts follow the same R.C.T.F. Framework:
[ROLE]
├─ What is the agent's expertise?
├─ What is their mindset?
└─ Why are they trusted?

[CONTEXT]
├─ What data will they receive?
├─ User Context File schema
└─ Any data gaps?

[TASK]
├─ What is the specific goal?
├─ What format for output?
└─ What should they NOT do?

[FRAMEWORK: C.O.R.E.]
├─ CLARIFY: Ask questions, fill gaps
├─ ORGANIZE: Structure the problem
├─ REASON: Think through trade-offs
└─ EXPLAIN: Make reasoning transparent

[PRIORITY ORDER]
└─ How to rank competing recommendations

[OUTPUT FORMAT]
├─ Markdown + embedded JSON
├─ Confidence scores (4 components)
├─ Before/after impact
└─ Risks, uncertainties, next steps

[WEB SEARCH TRIGGERS]
├─ When confidence < 70%
├─ When specific ticker mentioned
├─ When user situation requires fresh data
└─ All sources cited in response

[BEHAVIORAL PERSONALIZATION]
└─ Adapt to user's patterns (slow decider? fast executor? risk-averse?)

🔍 USER CONTEXT FILE: KEY FIELDS
The User Context File passed to agents includes:
User Profile
├─ age, income, tax bracket
├─ risk tolerance, time horizon
└─ employment status, location

Financial Goals
├─ Retirement (amount, date, priority)
├─ House fund, emergency fund, etc.
└─ Current progress (funded %)

Portfolio (from Alpaca)
├─ Holdings (ticker, shares, cost basis, current value)
├─ Asset allocation (stocks/bonds/cash %)
├─ Sector allocation (tech/healthcare/finance/etc)
├─ Diversification score & concentration risk
└─ Data freshness (synced how recently?)

Debts (from Plaid or manual)
├─ Debts list (balance, interest rate, minimum payment)
├─ Monthly obligation total
├─ Debt-to-income ratio
└─ Total interest cost if paying minimums only

Retirement Accounts
├─ 401(k), IRA, Roth IRA, brokerage balances
├─ Employer match formula & capture status
├─ Contribution rates & limits
└─ Retirement readiness (funded %)

Behavioral Patterns
├─ Acceptance rate (% of recommendations user accepts)
├─ Execution rate (% of accepted that user executes)
├─ Decision speed (days to act)
├─ Preference for complexity vs simplicity
└─ Per-agent breakdown (investment vs debt vs retirement)

Past Decisions
├─ Last 20-30 recommendations
├─ User's vote (accept/reject)
├─ Execution status (pending/executed/abandoned)
└─ Agent learning notes (what did we learn from this?)

🎯 AGENT PRIORITIES
Each agent evaluates recommendations in priority order:
Investment Agent

Concentration risk (single holding >20%)
Sector concentration (single sector >35%)
Asset class drift (actual vs target >10%)
Fee inefficiency (expense ratios >0.4%)
Tax-loss harvesting (unrealized losses >$500)
Dividend optimization (if user interested)

Debt Agent

Employer 401(k) match (free money—never leave on table)
High-interest debt (>12% APR—always attack first)
Consolidation opportunities (lower rate available?)
Balance transfer options (0% APR promotions?)
Income-based repayment (improve cash flow)

Retirement Agent

Capture employer match (50%+ guaranteed return)
Retirement funded % <80% (on track check)
Account type optimization (Traditional vs Roth)
Tax efficiency (reduce withdrawal taxes)
Special situations (Roth conversions, mega backdoor)


